{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"278a3280-71b2-4b90-9f4b-676bc19df0f9","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project itself is fine — a minimal .NET 8 console app. The developer report confirms the actual compilation is fast (<500ms) and incremental targets work. The overhead is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation.\n\nVisual Studio avoids this because it keeps a **long-lived MSBuild server process** in memory. The CLI starts a fresh process each time by default.\n\n### Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n**1. Use `dotnet watch` for inner-loop development**\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nKeeps a persistent process that watches for file changes — no repeated startup cost.\n\n**2. Enable the MSBuild Build Server**\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build          # first build warms the server\ndotnet build          # subsequent builds reuse it\n```\nThis gives CLI builds the same warm-server advantage Visual Studio has.\n\n**3. Skip restore when packages haven't changed**\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nAvoids NuGet evaluation overhead on every build.\n\n**4. Combine both flags for fastest ad-hoc builds**\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n### Why this matters\n\n| Approach | Startup overhead | Restore check | MSBuild eval |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet build` (default) | Every time | Every time | Every time |\n| `+ --no-restore` | Every time | Skipped | Every time |\n| `+ MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | Once | Every time | Cached |\n| `dotnet watch` | Once | Once | Cached |\n\nNo project file changes are needed — the bottleneck is entirely in the CLI invocation model, not the project configuration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"af156a98-48db-4ed5-97dd-71dbad7732e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer report says CLI builds are slow (2-4 seconds) even for no-op incremental builds, while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. The project is a simple .NET 8 console app.\n\nThe key insight here is the difference between how Visual Studio and the CLI handle builds:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** uses a long-lived MSBuild server process that keeps the project graph evaluated in memory, so subsequent builds skip the startup and evaluation overhead.\n\n2. **`dotnet build`** by default starts a fresh MSBuild process each time, which means:\n   - .NET SDK/runtime startup\n   - MSBuild process initialization\n   - Project file parsing and evaluation\n   - NuGet restore check\n   - Target execution (even if everything is up-to-date, the startup cost is paid)\n\nThe main solutions are enabling the MSBuild server to keep a background process running like Visual Studio does, skipping the restore phase with `--no-restore` when packages haven't changed to avoid NuGet overhead, or configuring MSBuild server settings directly in the project.\n\nFor development workflows with frequent rebuilds, `dotnet watch` keeps the process alive and uses file watchers to trigger incremental builds instead of paying the startup penalty each time. The most effective approach is enabling the MSBuild server through the environment variable, which eliminates the repeated startup and evaluation overhead across multiple invocations.","outputTokens":1132},"id":"b97d199d-59df-4fca-9105-7ed2d0d4c2f2","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:50:34.014Z","parentId":"999bf815-8c58-401f-b0a3-826623c0d666"}
